{{Redirect|Good cop|the British television show|Good Cop}}
{{other uses2|Good cop bad cop}}
'''"Good cop/bad cop" routine''', also called '''joint questioning''' or '''friend and foe''',<ref>See the declassified [[CIA]] ''Human Resource Exploitation Training Manual'' (1983), pp. 26-27. [http://www.gwu.edu/%7Ensarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB122/CIA%20Human%20Res%20Exploit%20H0-L17.pdf]</ref> is a psychological tactic used in [[negotiation]] and [[interrogation]].<ref>{{cite journal |title= Working Together but in Opposition: An Examination of the "Good-Cop/Bad-Cop" Negotiating Team Tactic |date= March 2000 |volume= 81 |issue= 2 |pages= 155–177 |journal= Organizational Behavior and Human Decision Processes |url= http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0749597899928790 |accessdate= 24 January 2015 |authors= Susan Brodt & Marla Tuchinsky |doi=10.1006/obhd.1999.2879}}</ref> "Good cop/bad cop" tactics involve a team of two interrogators who take apparently opposing approaches to the subject. The interrogators may interview the subject alternately or may confront the subject at the same time.

==Technique==
The "bad cop" takes an aggressive, negative stance towards the subject, making blatant accusations, derogatory comments, threats, and in general creating [[antipathy]] between the subject and himself. This sets the stage for the "good cop" to act sympathetically, appearing supportive and understanding, and in general showing [[sympathy]] for the subject. The good cop will also defend the subject from the bad cop. The subject may feel they can cooperate with the good cop either out of [[Trust (social sciences)|trust]] or out of fear of the bad cop. They may then seek protection by and trust the good cop and provide the information the interrogators are seeking.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sBvHPS8iNI4C&lpg=PA389&dq=good%20cop%20bad%20cop%20tactic&pg=PA389#v=onepage&q=good%20cop%20bad%20cop%20tactic&f=false |title= Promoting Community Change: Making it Happen in the Real World |publisher= Cengage Learning |year= 2010 |author= Mark Homan |isbn= 0840031955 |accessdate= 24 January 2015}}</ref>

This technique also has its disadvantages in that it can be easily identified and the "bad cop" may alienate the subject.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-1ZX88iEZIYC&lpg=PA114&ots=l82ixe-HCU&dq=good%20cop%20bad%20cop%20tactic&pg=PA115#v=onepage |title= Mastering Business Negotiation |year= 2011 |publisher= John Wiley & Sons |authors= Roy J. Lewicki & Alexander Hiam |isbn= 1118046943 |accessdate= 24 January 2015}}</ref>

